# PRACTICE: Styling links

Let's create a list of 3 links:

```html
<html>
  <body>
    <h2>Links</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <a href="/">home</a>
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/blog">blog</a>
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="<https://flaviocopes.com>">flaviocopes.com</a>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </body>
</html>

```

By default browsers render link in the blue color, and in that other color if a link has been *visited*:

![Screen Shot 2020-04-16 at 16.46.43.png](PRACTICE%20Styling%20links%201902767ad7e381c5ba29c7fbb71d9422/Screen_Shot_2020-04-16_at_16.46.43.png)

Yes, the browser maintains an internal state based on your visualization history.

We can style all links by targeting the `a` selector:

```css
a {
  color: black;
}

```

![Screen Shot 2020-04-16 at 16.59.39.png](PRACTICE%20Styling%20links%201902767ad7e381c5ba29c7fbb71d9422/Screen_Shot_2020-04-16_at_16.59.39.png)

You can style visited links by adding the `:visited` pseudo-class:

```css
a:visited {
  color: red;
}

```

![Screen Shot 2020-04-16 at 16.59.31.png](PRACTICE%20Styling%20links%201902767ad7e381c5ba29c7fbb71d9422/Screen_Shot_2020-04-16_at_16.59.31.png)

You can change the style of links you hover with the mouse using the `:hover` pseudo-class:

```css
a:hover {
  color: blue;
}

```

![Screen Shot 2020-04-16 at 16.59.26.png](PRACTICE%20Styling%20links%201902767ad7e381c5ba29c7fbb71d9422/Screen_Shot_2020-04-16_at_16.59.26.png)

